<subSubSection id="97C03CFDFF8EFF9DFF7EFDD0FBCDFC4C" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="description">
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF7EFDD0FD38FD18" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF7EFDD0FEE5FDFF" bold="true" box="[136,274,517,543]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Description</emphasis>
(from 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFE91FDD3FD3CFDC0" author="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G." box="[359,715,518,544]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="85 - 118" refId="ref33574" refString="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G. (2021) The genus Callitriche in south America. Phytotaxa 501 (1): 85 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 501.1.3" type="journal article" year="2021">Lansdown and Hassemer 2021</bibRefCitation>
):—Stem and leaf scales present. Leaf bases connate. Lingulate leaves unknown, expanded submerged or floating leaves unknown, leaves of terrestrial plants elliptic, (1–) 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFABEFDFFFA5BFDA4" box="[1352,1452,554,580]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 mm</quantity>
long × 0.8–2.3(–3.0) mm wide, 3-veined, petiole 0.5–2.0 mm long. Usually 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF8EFF9DFBF5FD9BFBBCFD88" box="[1027,1099,590,616]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="male">one ♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF8EFF9DFB7FFD9BFB26FD88" box="[1161,1233,590,616]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="female">one ♀</specimenCount>
flower together in most leaf axils, occasionally solitary. Bracts lacking. Styles recurved, caducous, ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFBC0FDA7FB7AFD6C" box="[1078,1165,626,652]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
long. Filaments erect, of undehisced stamens ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFE72FD43FE2DFD50" box="[388,474,662,688]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
long, of dehisced stamens ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFCE8FD43FC83FD50" box="[798,884,662,689]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
long; anthers quadrilocular, 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFB42FD43FACCFD50" box="[1204,1339,662,688]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="0.25" valueMax="0.4" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.4 mm</quantity>
diameter; pollen yellow. Fruits with pedicel ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFDEFFD6FFD99FD34" box="[537,622,698,724]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.6" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="6.6">6.6 mm</quantity>
long, not strumose, wider than high, black when mature, 0.5–1.0 mm long × 0.7–1.0 mm wide, wing up to 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFE06FD0BFDB1FD18" box="[496,582,734,760]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
throughout.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFCD4FC3EFCA0" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFCD4FEAEFCFB" bold="true" box="[189,345,769,795]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Illustrations:</emphasis>
—Plate 1169(13) in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFDCDFCD7FD2AFCFD" author="Fassett, N. C." box="[571,733,770,797]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="209 - 222" refId="ref31146" refString="Fassett, N. C. (1951) Callitriche in the New World. Rhodora 53: 137 - 155, 161 - 182, 185 - 194, 209 - 222, plates 1167 - 1175." type="journal article" year="1951">Fassett (1951)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF8EFF9DFD11FCD7FCB2FCFC" box="[743,837,770,796]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[136,229,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[166,1417,1167,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-458@13.[151,1436,1145,1870]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Dimensions of fruit of C. cyclocarpa and C. umbonata, numbers in brackets indicate the number of fruit measured, the line shows equal length and width" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577550" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577550/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
Figure 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFCC1FCD7FCB2FCFC" box="[823,837,770,796]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="in" value="8.0">8</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFC91FCD7FBCDFCFC" author="Bacigalupo, N. M." box="[871,1082,770,796]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="377 - 396" refId="ref29687" refString="Bacigalupo, N. M. (1979) El genero Callitriche en la flora argentina. Darwiniana 22: 377 - 396." type="journal article" year="1979">Bacigalupo (1979)</bibRefCitation>
. Figures on pages 140 and 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFA93FCD7FA5CFCFC" box="[1381,1451,770,796]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5814" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="in" value="141.0">141 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFF7EFCF3FEA6FCA0" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[136,337,806,832]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown (2008)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF8EFF9DFEABFCF3FE40FCA1" box="[349,439,806,833]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,225,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-31@4.[151,1436,190,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Fruits of Callitriche in Oceania and Australasia: a—C. antarctica, b—C. aucklandica, c—C. brachycarpa, d—C. brutia, e—C. capricorni, f—C. chathamensis, g—C. cyclocarpa i face on and ii end on, h—C. cycloptera, i—C. deflexa, j—C. fuliginea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577540/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(h) in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFDF6FCF3FC99FCA0" author="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G." box="[512,878,806,832]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="85 - 118" refId="ref33574" refString="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G. (2021) The genus Callitriche in south America. Phytotaxa 501 (1): 85 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 501.1.3" type="journal article" year="2021">Lansdown and Hassemer (2021)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF8EFF9DFC8FFCF3FC33FCA0" box="[889,964,806,832]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,225,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-31@4.[151,1436,190,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Fruits of Callitriche in Oceania and Australasia: a—C. antarctica, b—C. aucklandica, c—C. brachycarpa, d—C. brutia, e—C. capricorni, f—C. chathamensis, g—C. cyclocarpa i face on and ii end on, h—C. cycloptera, i—C. deflexa, j—C. fuliginea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577540/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Fig. 1i</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFC9CFBCDFC4C" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFC9CFEA1FC83" bold="true" box="[189,342,841,867]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Recognition:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF8EFF9DFE84FC9FFE13FC84" authorityName="A. Braun ex Hegelmaier" authorityYear="1864" box="[370,484,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deflexa">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFE84FC9FFE13FC84" box="[370,484,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">C. deflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF8EFF9DFC81FC9FFBBEFC84" box="[887,1097,842,868]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFC81FC9FFC07FC84" box="[887,1008,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Callitriche</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the region by the small fruit, most or all of which are long-pedicellate, blackish when mature and wider than high (although some fruit may be almost isodiametric, combined with both 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF8EFF9DFDAFFC47FD99FC4C" box="[601,622,914,940]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF8EFF9DFD53FC47FD4DFC4C" box="[677,698,914,940]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
flowers at least in the upper axils.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97C03CFDFF8EFF9DFF4BFC60FAD5FABC" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFC60FB62FB81" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFC60FEAEFC2F" bold="true" box="[189,345,949,975]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Distribution:</emphasis>
—Non-native to the region. Within the region, 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF8EFF9DFC9CFC63FBCBFC30" authorityName="A. Braun ex Hegelmaier" authorityYear="1864" box="[874,1084,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deflexa">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFC9CFC63FBCBFC30" box="[874,1084,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Callitriche deflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from flower beds in the Royal Botanical Gardens, Melbourne. Elsewhere, it is native to central South America in an area including southern 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFF07FC2BFECFFBF8" box="[241,312,1022,1048]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFEB2FC2BFE5AFBF8" box="[324,429,1022,1048]" name="Paraguay" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFE4CFC2BFDEBFBF8" box="[442,540,1022,1048]" name="Uruguay" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFD4CFC2BFCDAFBF8" box="[698,813,1022,1048]" name="Argentina" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. It is also very widespread as a non-native, with records from 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFF31FBF7FEC0FBDC" box="[199,311,1058,1084]" name="Mauritius" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFEB5FBF7FE5FFBDC" box="[323,424,1058,1084]" name="Morocco" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Morocco</collectingCountry>
(Cherrate Arboretum), 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFD40FBF7FCEFFBDC" box="[694,792,1058,1084]" name="Portugal" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Portugal</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFCD2FBF7FC41FBDC" box="[804,950,1058,1084]" name="South Africa" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFC35FBF7FBEFFBDC" box="[963,1048,1058,1084]" name="Taiwan" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFBD2FBF7FB7EFBDC" box="[1060,1161,1058,1084]" name="Tanzania" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFB1BFBF7FA5BFBDC" box="[1261,1452,1058,1084]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">United Kingdom</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF8EFF9DFF66FB93FEA4FB81" box="[144,339,1094,1121]" name="Ascension Island" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Ascension Island</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFE9FFB93FD3FFB80" author="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G." box="[361,712,1094,1120]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="85 - 118" refId="ref33574" refString="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G. (2021) The genus Callitriche in south America. Phytotaxa 501 (1): 85 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 501.1.3" type="journal article" year="2021">Lansdown and Hassemer 2021</bibRefCitation>
). See map on page 
<quantity id="1822C293FF8EFF9DFC56FB93FC10FB80" box="[928,999,1094,1120]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7338" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" unit="in" value="147.0">147 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFC18FB93FB66FB81" author="Fassett, N. C." box="[1006,1169,1094,1121]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="209 - 222" refId="ref31146" refString="Fassett, N. C. (1951) Callitriche in the New World. Rhodora 53: 137 - 155, 161 - 182, 185 - 194, 209 - 222, plates 1167 - 1175." type="journal article" year="1951">Fassett (1951)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFBBCFA68FB10" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFBBCFE30FB64" bold="true" box="[189,455,1129,1156]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Habitats and Ecology:</emphasis>
—In its native range, this species occurs in low-lying, humid areas such as sandy beaches and dry river beds. Outside its native range it occurs in a wide range of seasonally or permanently moist conditions such as irrigated areas of nurseries, ornamental beds and greenhouses in botanical gardens, low lying disturbed soil in areas such as unmetalled parking areas and on roadsides. There are no elevation data available from its native range.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFB2CFBD3FAD8" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFB2CFE4EFAF3" bold="true" box="[189,441,1273,1299]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Conservation Status:</emphasis>
—This species is widespread within its native range and there is no evidence that it faces any significant threats, it is therefore classed as Least Concern (LC) (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFC78FACBFBEEFAD8" author="IUCN &amp; Cambridge, UK" box="[910,1049,1310,1336]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" refId="ref32363" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK. 32 pp" type="book" year="2012">IUCN 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF8EFF9DFF4BFA94FAD5FABC" blockId="15.[136,1452,517,1372]" box="[189,1314,1345,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF8EFF9DFF4BFA94FDF0FABB" bold="true" box="[189,519,1345,1371]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258">Additional material studied</emphasis>
:—For a list of confirmed material, see 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF8EFF9DFC34FA97FAE9FABC" author="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G." box="[962,1310,1346,1372]" pageId="15" pageNumber="258" pagination="85 - 118" refId="ref33574" refString="Lansdown, R. V. &amp; Hassemer, G. (2021) The genus Callitriche in south America. Phytotaxa 501 (1): 85 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 501.1.3" type="journal article" year="2021">Lansdown and Hassemer 2021</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
